text.tspan: for the control of complex microscopes
Mick Phillips, David Miguel Susano Pinto, Richard M Parton, Nicholas Hall, Tiago Susano Pinto
Chris Weisiger, Andrew Jefferson, John W Sedat, Ilan Davis, and Ian M Dobbie

flowRoot.flowPara: Scientists that ought to be building microscopes are creating graphical interfaces to control their microscopes, and writing low-level software to control their devices. This software is often difficult to adapt to new hardware, impossible to maintain, or incur ongoing licensing costs. Effort is wasted as scientists in different labs solve the same problems independently. To address this, we have created Microscope and Cockpit.

Microscope is a Python package providing an abstract interface to different microscope devices with a focus on remote control and hardware triggering. Cockpit is a Python program that provides a graphical interface with a focus on scriptable experiments.
• The user interface connects to the devices it requires.
• Devices are in the network. They might be, or not, in the same computer as the user interface.
• Each device is a separate device server. The same computer can run any number of device servers.
• The same computer and user interface can control any number of microscopes.
• ctypes to interface with native libraries
• One process per device avoids the Python's GIL.
Mantas Žurauskas, Martin Booth, and Jordan Raff from the University of Oxford.
Julio Mateos Langerak from the Institute of Human Genetics, Montpellier.
